			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2025</a> paper:</span><br><i>Lessons Learned from Developing the MontiCore Language Workbench: Challenges of Modular Language Design</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NicoJansen.html">Nico Jansen</a>, <a href="../profile/AlexLüpges.html">Alex Lüpges</a>, <a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3732771.3742717">10.1145/3732771.3742717</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6a.html"><span class="tagM">T6A: Experience Reports</span></a><ul><li> It is explicitly framed as lessons learned from industrial-strength tool development, i.e., an experience report.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The focus is modular/compositional language development and integration, analyzing challenges in language composition.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> MontiCore is a language workbench, and the paper’s findings are grounded in its tooling architecture.
</li></ul></li></ul>
